1. What is the assignment operator in Java?
-->The assignment operator is:
👉 =
It is used to assign a value to a variable.
📌 Example:
int x = 10;   // assigns value 10 to x
✔ It takes the value on the right-hand side (RHS) and stores it in the left-hand side (LHS) variable.


2. What does x += y mean?
-->👉 x += y is a compound assignment operator
    It means:
    x = x + y;
    📌 Example:
    int x = 5;
    int y = 3;
    x += y;  // x = x + y → 5 + 3 = 8
    System.out.println(x); // 8
    ✔ Other similar operators:
    x -= y → x = x - y
    x *= y → x = x * y
    x /= y → x = x / y


3. Can you chain assignment operators like a = b = c = 10?
-->✔ Yes, you can chain assignments in Java

    📌 Example:
    
    int a, b, c;
    
    a = b = c = 10;
    
    System.out.println(a); // 10
    System.out.println(b); // 10
    System.out.println(c); // 10
    
    👉 How it works:
    
    c = 10 → assigns 10 to c
    b = c → assigns 10 to b
    a = b → assigns 10 to a

✔ Assignment happens right to left
